description:
'''New pop''' is a British-centric [[pop music]] movement consisting of ambitious, [[DIY ethic|DIY]]-minded artists who achieved commercial success in the early 1980s, aided by platforms like [[MTV]]. Rooted in the [[post-punk]] movement of the late 1970s, the movement encompassed a wide variety of styles and artists, including acts such as [[Orange Juice (band)|Orange Juice]], [[The Human League]], and [[ABC (band)|ABC]].

The term "[[rockism|rockist]]", a [[pejorative]] aimed at those who rejected this type of music, became associated with new pop.

"'''New music'''" is a similar but slightly more expansive [[umbrella term]]{{sfn|Reynolds|2005|p=338}} referring to a pop music and cultural phenomenon in the US tied to the [[Second British Invasion]]. The term was popularized by the music industry and American journalists during the 1980s to describe emerging movements such as new pop and [[New Romanticism]].{{sfn|Cateforis|2011|pp=12, 56}}
